As always, super quick turn around. I love it! Let’s sit down next week and figure this thing out together. Hopefully with the three of us in the room looking at the same thing we can figure out what’s wrong and fix it quickly. I know that our client will be really thrilled to have this sorted out before the start of the quarter. Let me know if there’s anything else I can do to help move this along.
Cheers,
David

Hey Support,
It was nice to work with you on Tuesday. I think we got most of the way there. Now that we’re rolling into Phase 2, I think I have a handle on the approximate price even without a contract in hand. There is the outstanding issue of the authentication API. I still think that one isn’t quite working correctly. I don’t think there’s much I can do to move this along with the client until we have that sorted it. It’s not like I can go to them and say we can go live in Beta without proper security in place. I heard that Dan suggested just downgrading from TLS to SSL, but I’m not okay with that approach. Please advice on our next steps when you have a free minute.

Cheers,
David

Hey Support Team,
Let’s look into that certificate issue first thing tomorrow. We are starting to get a little short on timeline to get this sorted out. I really appreciate the help because I know I wouldn’t be able to fix this by myself. I have openings at 9:00am and 11:00am. Let me know which will work best for you, but I’d really prefer to meet at 9:00am if we can. Drop me an email as soon as things are ready.
Cheers,
David

Support Team,

Awesome job! I had no idea that the authority chain could get messed up like that. Now that we’ve got that part all sorted out I think I can take this to the client and propose that the Beta is ready for launch. With the security certificate sorted out, there’s no SSL/TLS issues any more, and that means there’s no issues with the authentication APIs. Just to say it again, I couldn’t have figured this out without your help. Maybe next time I just need to book 90 minutes in the first place so that we can get right down to business and dig deep into it. In any event, as I said, your help was instrumental and now this thing is ready for takeoff. I’ll make sure to keep a close eye on the client experience and keep in touch if there are any other issues that emerge. I think there’s a really good chance that this seals the deal, gets us through Phase 2, and onto a possible Phase 3. Just to let you know, that Phase 3 might be worth as much as $300K over 3 months. Let’s keep working hard to make that a reality.
Sincerely,
David

person.Name: Anne Sokul
person.Emails:
Hello, This will be the last email I'm willing to send to this address. I believe I've sent 5 already and I'm yet to receive a response. If you cannot provide the required support please simply say so; however, if that's the case then I openly wonder why you sell the service at all. In the future, I would strongly advise better alignment between your sales organization and your delivery team. I'm disappointed with my overall experience, even if I did manage the get the first part working in the end. It's going to be hard to convince myself to work with you again or to recommend you to other contacts I have. Sincerely, Anne

Hi,
I guess that last email managed to (finally) get your attention. Why not just reply to the original emails? I appreciate having Greg reach out about the sales / delivery disconnect, but I really don’t think it should be on me to figure that out. I sell products to clients too. I have a deliver team too. It’s my job to make sure that’s running smoothly, not my client’s job. I know you know this as it’s pretty basic. So, here’s the scoop. If you’re interested in maintaining this contract, please have your CFO call me before end of day on Thursday.
Yours,
Anne

Hi Support,
Just so that you know, your CFO threw you under the bus hard. When he called me back – late, I might add – I made it pretty clear that the only way you were keeping the contract was by offering a 25% discount on the current contract price and offering a 10% discount on the renewal. He seemed less than inclined to see it my way; so I walked him through all of the business I’ve lost because of these issues. He's not happy and I’d certainly keep my head on a swivel if I were you. In the end, he managed to offer 15% for this contract and 5% for the renewal, but since that’s the difference between being in the red and being in the black over the next six quarters I had no choice but to turn him down. It’s been a disappointing experience overall and I really think a lot of the issues came down to how poorly your team interacts with both the sales and delivery organizations. If you want some free advice, consider this: even if sales and delivery were more on the same page, with the way you’re entirely siloed from both do you really think you can support questions coming from either side? I thought not. It’s a shame it went down this way, I don’t like that I’ve wasted $125K on this disaster, but I’m happy that I’ll be able to forego wasting another $275K by cutting out now. That’s right! Just so that you’re up to speed here, I am opting out of the rest of this contract. I’ll bite the bullet and figure something else out. But in this case having nothing is better than having you. How sad is that? Just pass along a quick message to Greg for me – if he ever wants I job I’d be more than happy to consider him. As far as I can tell, he’s the only competent person in your whole company. Maybe you’ll be ready to sell these kinds of services in a year or two, but by then I think the market will have dried up completely as it goes commodity. I really wish you’d managed to do a better job, I really like working with local companies as a general rule.
Anne
